WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.000
You know, usually when we talk about, like, a medical diagnosis, there's this underlying expectation of absolute precision.

00:07.320 --> 00:09.140
Oh, yeah, completely. We want it to be exact.

00:09.340 --> 00:17.060
Right. It's almost like engineering. You fall off your bike, you go to the hospital, and the x-ray shows that jagged white line on your radius bone.

00:17.200 --> 00:18.420
And there's no arguing with it.

00:18.720 --> 00:23.180
Exactly. The doctor just points at the screen and says, there it is. That's the break.

00:23.580 --> 00:27.640
It's incredibly satisfying because it's binary. It's clean.

00:27.640 --> 00:34.180
Yeah. I mean, it gives us a real sense of control. You identify the broken piece of the machine, you fix the piece, and the machine works again.

00:34.680 --> 00:39.360
We've built almost our entire modern worldview around that kind of mechanistic certainty.

00:39.620 --> 00:51.740
We really have. But then, you know, you step into the world of neurodevelopment or psychological trauma or even just trying to define what a memory actually physically is inside the brain.

00:51.900 --> 00:53.160
And that's where the certainty vanishes.

00:53.160 --> 01:00.480
Exactly. Suddenly, that x-ray machine is just totally useless. You're looking at a landscape that is incredibly murky. The boundaries blur.

01:00.760 --> 01:00.920
Yeah.

01:01.080 --> 01:12.780
And it makes you wonder, you know, what if the problem isn't that our instruments are too primitive? What if the problem is that we are using an x-ray to take a picture of a noun in a universe that only speaks in verbs?

01:12.780 --> 01:19.820
That is, I mean, that is the exact diagnostic muddy water that frames the monumental paradigm shift we're exploring today.

01:20.000 --> 01:20.700
It's a big one.

01:21.020 --> 01:31.220
Huge. Because we are deeply conditioned to want reality to be made of little billiard balls. We want things to be solid, persistent, and perfectly categorizable.

01:31.380 --> 01:32.880
Right. A universe of stuff.

01:32.880 --> 01:42.540
Exactly. Stuff. But the source material we're diving into today, which is this genuinely mind-bending paper from May 2026 by an author named Flyxion.

01:42.980 --> 01:47.100
Titled Process, Projection, and Propagative Reality, for those keeping track.

01:47.280 --> 01:51.800
Right. Well, this paper argues that this whole billiard ball view is a complete illusion.

01:51.940 --> 02:02.400
Let me tell you, if you are listening to this right now, maybe gripping your steering wheel or leaning against a kitchen counter, this paper's core mission is to prove that the solid object you are petching does not exist.

02:02.400 --> 02:04.040
At least not in the way you think it does.

02:04.320 --> 02:12.740
Yeah, not at all. Flyxion is taking on the very concept of substance itself. The paper proposes that absolutely nothing in the universe is static.

02:12.920 --> 02:13.760
Nothing at all.

02:13.800 --> 02:23.860
The chair you're sitting on, a memory of your childhood, the files on your computer, even the fundamental concept of a physical particle. None of these are things.

02:24.040 --> 02:24.700
They're processes.

02:24.900 --> 02:29.240
Exactly. There are continuous actions of what the paper calls recursive stabilization.

02:29.240 --> 02:39.640
It's an incredibly ambitious synthesis. I mean, the author is taking raw metaphysics and trying to give it a rigorous mathematical field-theoretic geometry.

02:39.840 --> 02:41.640
Which sounds intimidating, but it's fascinating.

02:41.900 --> 02:47.700
It is. And to do this, Flyxion weaves together philosophy, quantum mechanics, and advanced computer science.

02:48.180 --> 02:53.600
But the foundational layer of all this actually dates back to the late 1920s.

02:53.680 --> 02:54.320
Oh, really?

02:54.320 --> 03:03.700
Yeah, with a philosopher named Alfred North Whitehead. If we want to understand how a steering wheel is actually a verb, we really have to start with Whitehead's process ontology.

03:03.860 --> 03:10.840
Okay, well, let's unpack this. Because jumping from solid object to action of recursive stabilization is a massive leap to make.

03:11.060 --> 03:12.800
It's a total rewrite of how we think.

03:13.020 --> 03:22.580
It really is. So, if reality isn't made of enduring things, what exactly is the grammar of reality according to this framework?

03:22.580 --> 03:34.740
So, Whitehead proposed in his 1929 work, Process and Reality, that the fundamental units of existence are not enduring objects, but what he called actual occasions.

03:34.820 --> 03:35.720
Actual occasions.

03:35.960 --> 03:41.080
Right. Think of an actual occasion not as a noun, but as a completed act of becoming.

03:41.240 --> 03:41.520
Okay.

03:41.800 --> 03:44.380
It is a microscopic fleeting flash of existence.

03:44.620 --> 03:51.320
It comes into being, completes its internal process of organizing itself, and then it immediately perishes.

03:51.320 --> 03:52.480
Wait, it just vanishes?

03:52.640 --> 03:53.500
It perishes, yeah.

03:53.620 --> 03:59.140
That sounds incredibly chaotic. I mean, how does anything actually happen if reality is just a series of perishing flashes?

03:59.520 --> 04:03.480
Well, it doesn't vanish without a trace. When an occasion perishes, it becomes objective data.

04:03.720 --> 04:08.180
It basically becomes the raw, causal material for the next flash of existence.

04:08.300 --> 04:08.680
Oh, I see.

04:09.000 --> 04:12.400
Whitehead called this mechanism of inheritance prehension.

04:12.400 --> 04:25.280
So, the new actual occasion literally grasps or prehends the energetic and causal data from the occasions that just perished a fraction of a millisecond ago.

04:25.500 --> 04:33.300
I want to make sure I'm visualizing this inheritance correctly. It almost sounds like a rumor spreading through a massive crowd.

04:33.500 --> 04:35.020
That's a really good way to think about it.

04:35.020 --> 04:48.640
Like, when a rumor starts, it's highly volatile. One person hears a piece of information, another person hears a slight variation, and every time the rumor is passed to the next person, that new person is prehending the past versions.

04:49.060 --> 04:49.400
Yes.

04:49.760 --> 04:52.460
They are grasping the data from the person who just spoke.

04:52.580 --> 04:54.280
That captures the spirit of it perfectly.

04:54.440 --> 04:54.620
Yeah.

04:54.620 --> 04:59.580
Though, you know, mathematically, the paper takes us a step further through a concept called concrescence.

04:59.920 --> 05:01.260
Conqurescence. Let's define that.

05:01.440 --> 05:08.520
Well, when you hear that rumor, you aren't just a passive receiver. You're receiving multiple, sometimes conflicting accounts from different people.

05:08.600 --> 05:09.500
Right. You have to sort it out.

05:09.740 --> 05:11.480
Exactly. You have to integrate them.

05:11.540 --> 05:20.120
You have to resolve the tension of all that inherited data and stabilize it into a single, coherent narrative in your own mind before you pass it on.

05:20.180 --> 05:22.400
And that active resolution is concrescence.

05:22.520 --> 05:23.360
That's concrescence.

05:23.360 --> 05:33.600
So it's not just a copy-paste mechanism. The new occasion is actively taking the messy data of the past and locking it into a new, specific state.

05:33.740 --> 05:38.180
Precisely. And Flyxion formalizes this in the paper as a variational problem.

05:39.140 --> 05:44.040
Concrescence is modeled as a system finding a local minimum of inherited causal tension.

05:44.400 --> 05:45.360
Minimizing the tension.

05:45.420 --> 05:51.040
Right. The occasion is basically minimizing the deviation from the past data while maintaining its own internal consistency.

05:51.260 --> 05:51.560
Yeah.

05:51.560 --> 05:56.460
The satisfaction of the occasion is the exact moment it stabilizes into that agreed-upon state.

05:56.740 --> 05:57.180
Wow.

05:57.800 --> 06:02.740
And an enduring object like your steering wheel is just what Whitehead calls a nexus.

06:02.800 --> 06:03.260
A nexus.

06:03.260 --> 06:10.640
Yeah, it's a localized basin where this recursive inheritance of the same data keeps happening over and over, incredibly fast, in a stable way.

06:10.880 --> 06:13.000
Okay, I'm trying to square this with my everyday life.

06:13.380 --> 06:21.140
If everything is just a fleeting occasion of becoming, and my steering wheel is just a localized basin of rumors agreeing with each other.

06:21.220 --> 06:22.560
A very fast basin, yes.

06:22.560 --> 06:28.960
Right. Why does it feel so undeniably solid? I mean, why don't my hands just phase right through it?

06:28.960 --> 06:37.180
You're touching on the exact threshold where Whitehead's abstract philosophy requires the physics of the RSVP framework.

06:37.380 --> 06:39.880
Because philosophy isn't enough to build a car.

06:40.060 --> 06:47.280
Exactly. Whitehead gave us the metaphysics of flashes and inheritance, but that isn't enough to do modern physics.

06:47.280 --> 06:52.360
Flyxion translates this into continuous field dynamics using RSVP.

06:52.440 --> 06:56.400
Which stands for Recursive Stabilization of Volumetric Propagation. Right.

06:56.480 --> 06:56.920
Got it.

06:57.360 --> 07:01.020
It models reality using three continuously interacting fields.

07:01.480 --> 07:04.600
The scalar field, the vector field, and the entropy field.

07:04.720 --> 07:10.720
Okay, so we are upgrading from discrete momentary flashes to continuous flowing fluid dynamics.

07:10.720 --> 07:15.120
Let's define those three fields because I assume they are the invisible architecture of my steering wheel.

07:15.560 --> 07:16.320
They are indeed.

07:16.320 --> 07:20.460
The first is the scalar field, denoted by the Greek letter phi.

07:21.120 --> 07:25.700
You can basically think of this as configurational intensity or raw potential.

07:26.080 --> 07:28.360
Okay, phi is raw potential. Got it.

07:28.440 --> 07:34.900
The second is the vector field, represented by a lowercase v, which dictates directed flow and relational relaxation.

07:35.160 --> 07:36.120
Flow and relaxation.

07:36.300 --> 07:40.460
And finally, there is the S field, the entropy accessibility field.

07:40.580 --> 07:42.680
And these three aren't like separate layers.

07:43.060 --> 07:45.620
They are deeply coupled and interact constantly.

07:45.620 --> 07:48.240
So how do they make my steering wheel solid?

07:48.420 --> 07:53.100
In this framework, your steering wheel feels solid, not because it is made of inert matter,

07:53.460 --> 08:00.620
but because the continuous field configurations in that exact region of space have settled into a massive, tightly bound local attractor.

08:01.480 --> 08:02.180
An attractor.

08:02.480 --> 08:08.060
Meaning like a valley in a topographical map where all the water naturally wants to flow and pool together.

08:08.060 --> 08:09.640
That's a great way to visualize it.

08:10.320 --> 08:17.860
The structure of the wheel is persistent only because its specific energetic state is stably recoverable under recursive transport.

08:17.940 --> 08:18.700
Stably recoverable.

08:18.800 --> 08:19.020
Yeah.

08:19.360 --> 08:25.820
The fields are constantly flowing, constantly updating, but they are trapped in a tight loop of recursive inheritance.

08:25.820 --> 08:32.300
They keep regenerating the exact same coherent geometric pattern moment by moment.

08:32.360 --> 08:32.880
Wow.

08:32.880 --> 08:35.780
And the paper makes a profound assertion here.

08:36.240 --> 08:37.980
Identity is not primitive sameness.

08:38.520 --> 08:40.480
Identity is just stable recoverability.

08:40.480 --> 08:44.620
So the steering wheel isn't a thing that exists from one second to the next.

08:44.780 --> 08:50.960
It is a pattern that the universe is just extremely relentlessly good at remembering how to recreate.

08:51.680 --> 08:52.420
It's an action.

08:52.600 --> 08:53.960
It is dynamic coherence.

08:54.740 --> 09:02.480
And if we follow this logic to really understand this stable recoverability, we have to look closely at the S and the RSVP framework.

09:03.380 --> 09:04.100
The entropy feel.

09:04.100 --> 09:04.480
Right.

09:04.660 --> 09:14.160
Because how Flyxion defines entropy completely radically changes how we view the passage of time, the future, and even the deepest mysteries of quantum mechanics.

09:14.300 --> 09:14.420
Okay.

09:14.500 --> 09:18.700
Well, if the universe is just continuously regenerating patterns, what does that mean for the future?

09:18.800 --> 09:22.060
Because usually when I hear the word entropy, I'm thinking about thermodynamics.

09:22.240 --> 09:23.360
Like heat loss and disorder.

09:23.680 --> 09:23.960
Yeah.

09:24.120 --> 09:31.060
I'm thinking about my office getting messier over the week or a coffee mug shattering on the floor and never spontaneously reassembling itself.

09:31.360 --> 09:32.940
Entropy is disorder.

09:32.940 --> 09:35.700
That is the standard thermodynamic definition.

09:35.960 --> 09:36.200
Yes.

09:36.840 --> 09:44.320
But in the RSVP field equations, entropy capital S is stripped of that messiness connotation entirely.

09:44.520 --> 09:45.060
Oh, really?

09:45.340 --> 09:45.560
Yes.

09:45.720 --> 09:49.320
Lickshan defines it purely geometrically as accessibility volume.

09:50.040 --> 09:51.120
Accessibility volume.

09:51.280 --> 09:52.580
You're going to have to translate that for me.

09:52.760 --> 09:54.060
What exactly is accessible?

09:54.460 --> 09:55.140
The future.

09:55.300 --> 09:55.780
The future.

09:56.220 --> 10:01.880
Specifically, it is the logarithmic volume of admissible future trajectories available to a system.

10:01.880 --> 10:02.320
Okay.

10:02.420 --> 10:03.620
I think I need a visual for that.

10:03.840 --> 10:06.960
Imagine you are standing in the center of a massive empty field.

10:07.620 --> 10:09.520
Your S value is extremely high.

10:09.920 --> 10:13.200
You could walk north, south, east, west, or any angle in between.

10:13.300 --> 10:14.300
So I have a lot of options.

10:14.420 --> 10:14.760
Exactly.

10:15.300 --> 10:17.640
The volume of your possible futures is vast.

10:18.320 --> 10:21.900
But now imagine you are standing at the bottom of a narrow, steep canyon.

10:22.220 --> 10:23.420
I can't really go left or right.

10:23.800 --> 10:24.240
Exactly.

10:24.360 --> 10:26.220
Your S value is very low.

10:26.220 --> 10:29.740
You can only walk forward or backward along the canyon floor.

10:30.140 --> 10:33.860
The geometry of your accessible future is highly constrained.

10:34.360 --> 10:34.460
Okay.

10:34.600 --> 10:39.400
So it's quite literally a physical geometry of possible choices or outcomes.

10:39.640 --> 10:39.860
Yes.

10:40.140 --> 10:45.580
And here is where Flyxion applies this to the famous problem of quantum collapse.

10:45.960 --> 10:46.440
Oh, man.

10:46.660 --> 10:47.340
Quantum collapse.

10:47.420 --> 10:48.300
That's always a headache.

10:48.480 --> 10:48.600
Right.

10:48.600 --> 10:53.860
Well, in traditional quantum mechanics, a particle like an electron exists in a superposition.

10:54.420 --> 10:57.960
It's theoretically in many possible states or locations at once.

10:58.280 --> 10:58.420
Right.

10:58.740 --> 11:04.480
Then, mysteriously, when a human observes it or a machine measures it, the wave function

11:04.480 --> 11:07.100
collapses into one definite classical state.

11:07.220 --> 11:09.440
Which has confused people for, what, a century?

11:09.700 --> 11:10.560
Literally a century.

11:10.940 --> 11:13.560
Physicists have debated the mechanism of this collapse constantly.

11:13.940 --> 11:15.300
Does human consciousness cause it?

11:15.540 --> 11:17.320
Are there parallel universes splitting off?

11:17.320 --> 11:17.620
Right.

11:17.700 --> 11:19.800
The classic Schrodinger's cat thought experiment.

11:19.940 --> 11:23.800
The cat is mathematically both alive and dead until you open the box and force the universe

11:23.800 --> 11:24.700
to make up its mind.

11:24.840 --> 11:25.260
Exactly.

11:26.100 --> 11:30.600
But Flyxion argues that this entire problem is just a misunderstanding of accessibility.

11:31.120 --> 11:31.280
Yeah.

11:31.620 --> 11:33.500
We don't need a magical collapse postulate.

11:33.780 --> 11:38.120
And we certainly don't need human observation to force reality into a definite state.

11:38.240 --> 11:39.440
So what's actually happening?

11:39.440 --> 11:48.400
Instead, this transition from a blurry, superposed quantum state to a definite macroscopic classical

11:48.400 --> 11:54.440
state happens naturally because alternative future trajectories simply lose their accessibility

11:54.440 --> 11:55.180
geometry.

11:55.740 --> 12:00.420
I'm tracking with the canyon analogy, but how does a superposed trajectory lose its geometry

12:00.420 --> 12:01.700
in the actual physics?

12:02.080 --> 12:03.640
Does the canyon wall just close in?

12:03.640 --> 12:04.800
In a way, yes.

12:05.200 --> 12:11.720
As the RSVP fields recursively couple and interact with each other, their dynamics naturally constrain

12:11.720 --> 12:12.940
the available phase space.

12:13.080 --> 12:13.340
Okay.

12:13.560 --> 12:19.100
The paper proves mathematically that the volume of classical superposed futures naturally shrinks

12:19.100 --> 12:21.240
over time due to recursive field interactions.

12:21.460 --> 12:22.760
It just naturally gets smaller.

12:22.980 --> 12:23.180
Right.

12:23.180 --> 12:27.800
Eventually, the definite classical volume becomes vastly smaller than the superposed volume.

12:28.700 --> 12:31.660
The world isn't violently forced into one state by a measurement device.

12:32.260 --> 12:36.980
Rather, the recursively recoverable alternatives simply vanish from the admissible future.

12:37.300 --> 12:38.040
They just fade out.

12:38.420 --> 12:38.760
Exactly.

12:38.920 --> 12:41.100
There are no longer mathematically accessible paths.

12:41.180 --> 12:41.320
Yeah.

12:41.600 --> 12:42.820
The S field contracts.

12:43.260 --> 12:47.280
So reality is basically pruning the tree of possible futures.

12:47.660 --> 12:50.020
It's not chopping off branches with an axe.

12:50.020 --> 12:54.700
The branches are just dissolving until only one thick, solid trunk remains.

12:54.860 --> 12:56.200
That's a beautiful way to phrase it.

12:56.520 --> 13:02.060
And the paper outlines three distinct regimes of process organization based on how this entropy

13:02.060 --> 13:02.840
field behaves.

13:03.320 --> 13:05.480
The first is harmonic lock.

13:05.920 --> 13:06.920
Harmonic lock.

13:06.980 --> 13:08.360
That sounds incredibly secure.

13:08.500 --> 13:10.080
I assume this is the thick trunk of the tree.

13:10.280 --> 13:10.780
It is.

13:10.920 --> 13:14.960
In harmonic lock, the accessibility volume is very low and actively contracting.

13:15.540 --> 13:19.180
The system is tightly constrained to a very small basin of attraction.

13:19.180 --> 13:20.820
So there aren't many paths left.

13:21.060 --> 13:21.540
Hardly any.

13:21.880 --> 13:26.260
It is highly predictable, meaning the deviation from its expected continuation is near zero.

13:26.780 --> 13:29.380
This is the regime of solid objects of classical physics.

13:29.640 --> 13:30.340
So my steering wheel.

13:30.500 --> 13:30.740
Yes.

13:31.140 --> 13:33.860
Your steering wheel is in a state of deep harmonic lock.

13:34.040 --> 13:34.420
Got it.

13:34.520 --> 13:35.300
And the second regime?

13:35.540 --> 13:37.880
The second is the bounded stochastic field.

13:38.760 --> 13:43.780
Here, the accessibility volume is moderate and bounded, but it's not actively collapsing into

13:43.780 --> 13:44.560
a single point.

13:44.820 --> 13:46.340
So it's still moving around a bit.

13:46.400 --> 13:46.560
Right.

13:46.560 --> 13:49.100
The system is wandering around within a constrained envelope.

13:49.180 --> 13:54.920
It has a definite overall character, but its exact moment-to-moment position is chaotic

13:54.920 --> 13:56.120
within those bounds.

13:56.820 --> 13:59.360
Think of a moth trapped inside a glass jar.

14:00.080 --> 14:04.800
You know it's in the jar, but you cannot predict exactly where in the jar it will be from one

14:04.800 --> 14:05.720
millisecond to the next.

14:05.820 --> 14:05.940
Okay.

14:06.060 --> 14:08.480
Harmonic lock is the solid steering wheel.

14:09.120 --> 14:11.200
Bounded stochastic is the moth in the jar.

14:11.440 --> 14:12.180
What's the third?

14:12.380 --> 14:14.100
The third is the impulsive reset.

14:14.100 --> 14:16.900
This is a Dirac-like spike in the equations.

14:17.740 --> 14:21.120
The accessibility volume briefly maximizes.

14:21.740 --> 14:26.920
The future basically blows wide open, expanding rapidly, and then it suddenly discontinuously

14:26.920 --> 14:27.460
collapses.

14:27.620 --> 14:27.860
Wow.

14:27.980 --> 14:29.680
Just blows open and slams shut?

14:29.840 --> 14:30.300
Exactly.

14:30.640 --> 14:34.640
It resets the entire admissibility structure before the system settles back into either a

14:34.640 --> 14:37.100
harmonic lock or a bounded stochastic state.

14:37.100 --> 14:41.400
You know, when I read the paper, the impulsive reset was the hardest part to grasp until Flyxion

14:41.400 --> 14:44.240
introduced an analogy that I found absolutely staggering.

14:44.500 --> 14:45.340
Oh, the audio one.

14:45.660 --> 14:45.980
Yes.

14:46.580 --> 14:53.320
The paper connects these three physical regimes to audio signal processing, specifically a

14:53.320 --> 14:55.020
technique called deadband compression.

14:55.360 --> 15:01.260
The deadband compression analogy is a phenomenal bridge between the abstract math and practical

15:01.260 --> 15:01.700
engineering.

15:02.160 --> 15:03.960
Why don't you walk us through how you understood it?

15:03.960 --> 15:08.940
Okay, so imagine you're an audio encoder, and your job is to stream a live sound over

15:08.940 --> 15:09.380
the internet.

15:09.920 --> 15:15.920
In traditional uncompressed systems, you have to send a packet of data for every single

15:15.920 --> 15:17.660
microsecond of the sound wave.

15:17.820 --> 15:19.240
Just a constant stream of data.

15:19.300 --> 15:19.400
Right.

15:19.640 --> 15:21.720
Constantly shouting, here's the pitch, here's the volume.

15:22.320 --> 15:24.840
But in deadband compression, the system is smarter.

15:25.400 --> 15:30.200
It only transmits data when the audio signal actually deviates from what the algorithm already

15:30.200 --> 15:31.420
predicted it was going to do.

15:31.500 --> 15:32.020
Makes sense.

15:32.020 --> 15:37.280
So if the audio is perfectly predictable, like a synthesizer holding a steady, continuous,

15:37.560 --> 15:41.200
middle C note, the encoder stops sending data entirely.

15:41.400 --> 15:42.720
It just transmits silence.

15:42.880 --> 15:44.660
Because the receiver already knows what's happening.

15:44.740 --> 15:45.000
Right.

15:45.280 --> 15:46.740
But here's where it gets really interesting.

15:47.320 --> 15:50.780
In that data stream, the silence doesn't mean the song has stopped.

15:51.140 --> 15:53.480
The silence means perfect predictability.

15:53.860 --> 15:54.260
Exactly.

15:54.660 --> 15:56.900
The system is in a perfect harmonic lock.

15:57.360 --> 16:01.700
The receiver algorithm is just coasting on the assumption that the tone will continue.

16:02.420 --> 16:07.340
The sender doesn't need to waste bandwidth saying, it's still middle C, it's still middle C.

16:07.440 --> 16:08.800
It saves all that energy.

16:09.000 --> 16:09.460
Exactly.

16:09.780 --> 16:16.180
It only sends a sudden burst of data, an impulsive reset, when the musician suddenly changes the

16:16.180 --> 16:16.520
chord.

16:17.020 --> 16:22.260
The paper makes the argument that this kind of compression ratio isn't just a clever software

16:22.260 --> 16:23.040
design choice.

16:23.040 --> 16:24.240
No, it's much bigger than that.

16:24.300 --> 16:28.240
It is a fundamental structural consequence of the geometry of the universe.

16:28.580 --> 16:34.460
And if we map that back to the physics of the RSVP framework, it fundamentally changes

16:34.460 --> 16:37.340
how we view information and existence itself.

16:37.400 --> 16:38.260
It's wild.

16:38.980 --> 16:41.940
Silence in the data stream is not the absence of reality.

16:42.420 --> 16:45.000
It is the presence of sustained harmonic lock.

16:45.000 --> 16:50.320
The physical universe doesn't need to expend thermodynamic energy computing the next state

16:50.320 --> 16:52.960
of your steering wheel from scratch every millisecond.

16:53.060 --> 16:54.360
Because it's already locked in.

16:54.460 --> 16:54.860
Exactly.

16:55.420 --> 17:00.880
The admissibility field is so tightly constrained, the canyon is so narrow, that all future continuations

17:00.880 --> 17:02.500
are functionally indistinguishable.

